Slight modification of MetricsServlet to catch Exception instead of just JsonMappingException in gauge evaluations. If a gauge throws an exception in a relatively small response, Jetty catches it before any buffers are flushed and returns an HTTP 500 with a suitable error page. If a gauge throws an exception in a larger response, after some of the buffer has been flushed to the client, Jetty cuts off the response stream, resulting in an HTTP 200 with a partial JSON response.This modification to MetricsServiet allows a gauge to throw an exception and not trigger a cut off JSON response.n

Correctly handle non-US locales for Graphite reportingGraphite expects floats formatted as 1.09. String.format usesnLocale.getDefault, which may not be a US locale, and may use a differentndecimal separator, such as fr-CA, which uses 1,09.nnCarbon-cache, Graphite's data store, will ignore any lines which itncan't parse, thus preventing metrics from entering the database.n

Added support for Guice to create an MeterMetric to monitor exceptionsWhen instrumenting classes with the annotations in metrics-guice, it isnsometimes desirable to count the number of times a method has failed.nPreviously, this resulted in lots of occurences of the following pattern:nn@Meterednpublic void doBlah() throws MyException {n  try {n...n  } catch (MyException e) {nfailureMetric.mark();nthrow e;n  }n}nnThis commit introduces a new annotation @ExceptionMetered to thenmetrics-guice module. This new annotation has similar semantics to thenexisting @Metered annotation, but instead of counting invocations of thendecorated method, it counts the number of invocations that resulted innan exception being thrown. It can be used in conjunction with thenexisting @Metered and @Timed annotation. For example, the above examplencan be written as:nn@Meteredn@ExceptionMetered(cause=MyException.class)npublic void doBlah() throws MyException {n...n}nnAs usual, the new annotation takes arguments to modify the name andnunits of the metric. Using the cause field, it is possible tonspecify the type of Throwable (defaults to java.lang.Exception) thatnthe instrumentation will capture.n

Refactor how reporters interact with metrics.= OriginnThe core of this refactoring is the introduction of the MetricsProcessorninterface which now all the reporters implement. The primary driver herenis to eliminate a slew of code blocks following this pattern:nnif(metric instanceof Timer) {n...n} else if(metric instanceof Counter) {n...n}n...etc...nnSo there's now a MetricsProcessor that solves this and forces it'snimplementors to handle all different metric types. An effect of this is thatnintroducing a new type of metric will trickle down to all reporters andnimplementors of this is interface.nn= Collateral changesnIn the process of getting this in place the following has also happened:n- New interface: Summarized that groups min(), max(), mean(), stdDev()n- New interface: Percentiled that groups percentile(double) andn  percentiles(Double...)n- A lot of tests for reporters have been added (thanks to @jebl01)n- Utils.sortAndFilterMetrics() now returns the MetricName in its resultn- Added Utils.filterMetrics() to only filter based on a MetricPredicatennThe two new interfaces also allowed elimination of duplication in somenof the reporters.n

Totally revamp metrics-core.Big new changes:nn* Meter and timers no longer have units. Units will be the responsibility of reporters.n* Metrics are identified by dotted names, not quasi-ObjectNames.n* Reporting architecture has been radically simplified.n* You can register metrics not created by the registry.n* Separated health checks into their own modules.n* No more default registries.nnI've pinned the other modules to metrics-core 2.2.0 to make a progressive upgrade easier.n

add an instrumented ScheduledExecutorServiceThe instrumented decorator for ScheduledExecutorService follows the instrumented decorator ExecutorService. It uses the same four metrics, as well as adding an additional four.nnThe original four:n- submitted: is a meter only for invocations of `execute`, `submit`, `invokeAll`, and `invokeAny`.n- running: is a counter for *all* running tasks.n- completed: is a meter for *all* task completions.n- duration: is a timer for the execution time of *all* tasks.nnThe new four:n- scheduled.once: is a meter only for invocations of `schedule`.n- scheduled.repeatedly: is a meter only for invocations of `scheduleAtFixedRate` and `scheduleWithFixedDelay`.n- scheduled.overrun: is a counter for tasks started by `scheduleAtFixedRate`. The counter is incremented whenever the execution time of a task is greater than the scheduled period (thus causing delayed execution of the next task).n- percent-of-period: is a histogram for tasks started by `scheduleAtFixedRate` and records the execution time of a task as a percentage of the scheduled period.n

If the JDK provides ThreadLocalRandom, use it. Otherwise,rnfallback to the internal implementation.rnrn* Support JDK's LongAdder (#1055)rnrn* Support the JDK's LongAdderrnrnAdd an ability to use the JDK's implementation if it's available in thernruntime. Use a proxy for creating LongAdders which tries to use the JDK'srnimplementation and fallbacks to the internal one if the JDK doesn'trnprovide any.rnrnUnfortunatelly, `LongAdder`s don't have a common interface, therefore wernintroduce `LongAdderAdapter` as a common interface for `LongAdder`s. Fix for the monitoring jetty9 async servlet requests. (#1074)Async requests are monitored via the addition of an async listener.rnThe bug was that `onStartAsync(AsyncEvent)` is called when the handlerrninvokes `startAsync()` but the `InstrumentedHandler` only added thernlistener after the call to the delegate handler, thus would missrnthe all onStartAsync event.rnrnThe net result of the bug was that the start time of all async requestsrnwas reported as 0 so the calculated elapsed times where then ratherrnlarge (i.e. currentTimeMillis()).

Add support for overriding format of floating numbers in Graphite (#1073)Currently, we trim all decimal values to 2 digits after the point. Despiternthat's a good default, some applications require reporting floating numbersrnwith better precision.rnrnFor those users we provide the ability to override the `format(double v)`rnmethod of `GraphiteReporter`. User can provide a custom format (or just userna plain double-to-string conversion). We also need to make the constructorrnof `GraphiteReporter` protected, because users can't override a class withrna private constructor.

Pools that don't support collectionrnusage statistics will skip this metric.rnrn(cherry picked from commit d416365)rnrn* Opt-in default shared registryrnrn(cherry picked from commit 83fe8d3)rnrn* Use same string instance for rateUnit across all instances that have the same TimeUnit.rnrnhttps://github.com/dropwizard/metrics/issues/802rnrn(cherry picked from commit f8639b8)rnrn* use String.intern instead of our own maprnrn(cherry picked from commit 716824a)rn(cherry picked from commit 524bb6b)rnrn* Add support for patterns in MBean object namesrnrnIf the object name is a pattern, perform a query for matching objectrnnames and return the value of the given attribute if the pattern yieldsrna unique match. Move closing` DatagramChannel` to the close method (#1080)We can align `GraphiteUDP` with the TCP based `Graphite` and close thernsocket in the `close` method instead of the connect method. The closernmethod will be invoked every time after a portion of metrics has beenrnsent, so we can close the socket there. We also do not need to callrnthe method `isConnected` during sending metrics because the socket isrnopened right before sending data, so it can't be closed by timeout.

Fix creating a uniform snapshot from a collection (#1111)The current code for creating a snapshot from the collection is unfortunately broken.rnThe code fails if the provided collection is modified during creating of the snapshot andrnit has a weak iterator (precisely what `ConcurrentSkipListMap` provides). The iteratorrndoesn't guarantee that it has exactly the same amount iteration as the size of therncollection. As a result, the code throws an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundException`.rnThe correct behaviour is too dump the collection to a resizable array on the fly andrnthen convert it the array of long primitives.rnrnThe behaviour was correct in the 3.1 branch, but was broken in 3.2 by the optimizationrnin #972.

Fix a racy read bug in EWMABecause `rate` is only volatile, but not an atomic primitive, itsnupdates are racy. The problem with the current code is that we readn`rate` twice before making a  write. That means we could calculate anchange relying on one rate, but add it to another. The fix is to readn`rate` to a local variable and calculate a new value based on it. Thisnguarantees that the new rate is based only one rate and produces ancorrect value. We still have a lost update problem, but it's notnimportant, because it doesn't matter how many threads update the ratensimultaneously. They all set the same new rate based on the currentncount.n

Improve performance of ChunkedAssociativeLongArrayAs suggested by errorprone, it's almost never a good idea to use an`LinkedList`. The biggest problem with it is that it has a very bigncost of traversal (more 4 times bigger than the cost of removing annelemt from an array). Considering iteration is more often than removingnin trimming, it makes sense just to use an array-based queue, becausenit has a predictable-perfomance.nnhttp://errorprone.info/bugpattern/JdkObsoletenhttps://stuartmarks.wordpress.com/2015/12/18/some-java-list-benchmarks/n

Adding in a duration field to the healthcheck result (#1360)

Improve calculation of Health check durations (#1361)Use `System.nanotime` instead of `System.currentTimeMillis`.rnDifference between invocations of System.currentTimeMillis() canrnproduce negative values depending of how CPU clock synchronizationrnworks in different environments. The standard pattern is to usern`System.nanotime` which is monotonous.

Add ability to provide custom clocks for HealthCheck (#1362)Use the `Clock` abstraction from `metrics-core` for that. Usersrncan override the `clock` method in their health checks. For example,rnit's useful for pinning the clock in unit tests.
Make HealthCheck more stable for unit testing (#1363)Don't use duration in equals & hashCode because it's a calculated field.
Improve HealthCheckServletTest (#1364)Pin down the clock in the health checks, so we can be sure that arnduration is zero.

Include timestamp in serialized JSON output for HealthCheck.Result (#1365) (#1366)- Include timestamp in JSON output from HealthCheckModulern- Update HealthCheckModuleTestrn- Update HealthCheckServletTest (since actual timestamp is from arn  ZonedDateTime.now() call in HealthCheck.Result's private constructor,rn  the test cannot easily match the exact timestamp. More refactoringrn  would need to be done to permit using a mock Clock in order torn  do that. As a result the tests now verify the presence of thern  timestamp but not the actual value)

Add clock to result builder (#1372)* Add JDK9 module name for metrics-logback (#1368)rnrn* Add ability to provide a custom Clock to health check ResultBuilderrnrn- Add Clock argument to private HealthCheck.Result constructorsrn- Use Clock.defaultClock() as the default clock in HealthCheck.Resultrn- Use the Clock instance to obtain the current time for the timestamprn  in HealthCheck.Result private constructorrn- Add a Clock to HealthCheck.ResultBuilder with Clock.defaultClock() asrn  the default valuern- Add usingClock(Clock) to HealthCheck.ResultBuilder to allow customizingrn  the Clock when using the builder to create health check Resultsrn- Add test of ResultBuilder#usingClock in HealthCheckTestrn- Update toString test in HealthCheckTest making use ofrn  ResultBuilder#usingClock so that the timestamp can be included in thern  equality checkrn- Add a new test of the ResultBuilder#withMessage(String, Object...) methodrn  in HealthCheckTest (because IntelliJ flagged it as not used)rn- Update HealthCheckServletTest to use ResultBuilder#usingClock so thatrn  the assertions can include the timestamp and check the entire responsern  content of the health checkrnrnIn both HealthCheckTest and HealthCheckServletTest I duplicated therndate/time pattern from HealthCheck.Result, which is not ideal, but isrnbetter than exposing the Result's private Pattern. Unless the patternrnis also made configurable, this seemed like a decent trade-off.rn
